{"key":"processedPost-19740672","value":{"id":19740672,"first":19740301,"last":19741022,"when":1395685279,"utime":"03/24/14 09:21 PM","content":"The only reason you had a higher contamination rate is because of using fresh coffee grinds in a bulk substrate.&nbsp; Once you get it damp, the coffee 'brews' and spits too much liquid coffee into your bulk substrate.&nbsp; Always use spent coffee grinds as a bulk substrate ingredient and save the fresh coffee for grains.<br />To the OP, I use coffee grinds every day, but after brewing, they get mixed into the rest of the substrate and pasteurized or sterilized together.&nbsp; Do the same thing after thawing out frozen ones.&nbsp; Since coffee grinds are too nutritious as a substrate by themselves, you're always going to be mixing them with something else so pasteurize it all together.<br />RR","title":"Re: Pasteurizing Coffee"}}